      {
        "id": 2330737,
        "name": null,
        "username": "g.colangelo",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/d6d6ee/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2018-01-06T08:32:02.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"JW Boyden\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n JW Boyden:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Opened one of these yesterday to see which side of the coin I came down on. The fruit here is massive for a Burgundy. My friend initially thought I served him a west coast pinot when tasted blind. If you look hard enough behind the fruit you do get Gevrey spice, some mineral, and the texture is reasonably silky like most Fourrier wines. With air the fruit seemed to move to a more stewed/cooked character. I am going to let my remaining bottles sit for some time and see if these can shed some baby fat and come into a bit better balance for my palate.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>My impression from a recent Burgundy 2015 tasting was similar to this one, too massive for me to be enjoyed now, and I usually very much like Fourrier, even when young. Interestingly, I found his 1er cru Champeaux to be better balanced than the village. But in this vintage I preferred other producers with a lighter hand\u2026</p>",
